{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477022"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:55:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:55:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14141"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14141"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.02,0.26,0.02,0.67]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6821"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55906"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6821"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14141"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41455"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1643"},{"type":"tags","id":"2108"},{"type":"tags","id":"2375"},{"type":"tags","id":"2756"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"11696"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15383"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55906"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of spontaneous bruising and petechiae on his legs. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are multiple petechiae on his lower legs and a few scattered bruises on his arms. The remainder of the physical examination is unremarkable. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete blood count:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 120 g/L (110-140)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite Cell Count (WCC): 6.0 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (5.0-15.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 20 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReticulocytes: 1.2% (0.5-2.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeripheral blood smear:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets appear large (megathrombocytes)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoagulation profile:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProthrombin Time (PT): 12 seconds (11-15)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInternational Normalised Ratio (INR): 1.0 (0.8-1.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EActivated Partial Thromboplastin Time (aPTT): 30 seconds (25-35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver function tests:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT: 22 U/L (5-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST: 20 U/L (15-55)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin: 40 g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectrolytes urea creatinine:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium: 140 mmol/L (133-146)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrea: 3.2 mmol/L (1.8-6.4)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine: 45 \u00b5mol/L (21-36)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR: \u0026gt;90 mL/min/1.73m^2 (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinalysis:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProtein: Negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENitrites: Negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: Negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypersplenism","Drug-induced thrombocytopenia","Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura","Disseminated intravascular coagulation","Immune thrombocytopenia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis for this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmune thrombocytopenia (ITP)\u003C/strong\u003E. The clinical presentation of spontaneous bruising and petechiae, along with isolated severe thrombocytopenia (platelets 20 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L) and normal haemoglobin and white cell count, is characteristic of ITP. The peripheral blood smear showing large platelets (megathrombocytes) is also consistent with this diagnosis, as it indicates increased platelet production in response to peripheral destruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura (TTP)\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a pentad of thrombocytopenia, microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, neurological symptoms, renal dysfunction, and fever. This patient\u0027s normal haemoglobin, renal function, and lack of neurological symptoms make TTP less likely. Additionally, TTP is rare in children.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC)\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by consumption of coagulation factors and platelets, leading to both bleeding and clotting. It would typically show abnormal coagulation studies (prolonged PT and aPTT), which are normal in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrug-induced thrombocytopenia\u003C/strong\u003E is a possibility in any case of isolated thrombocytopenia, but this patient has no history of medication use. If present, it would be indistinguishable from ITP based on these results alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypersplenism\u003C/strong\u003E can cause thrombocytopenia, but it typically causes pancytopenia (reduction in all blood cell lines) rather than isolated thrombocytopenia. The normal haemoglobin and white cell count make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe normal liver function tests help rule out liver disease as a cause of thrombocytopenia. The normal renal function and urinalysis make renal causes unlikely. The diagnosis of ITP is primarily one of exclusion, and further testing (such as anti-platelet antibodies) may be performed to support the diagnosis, although these are not always necessary or definitive. ITP is more common in children than adults, with a peak incidence between two and five years of age, which further supports this diagnosis in this three-year-old boy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Isolated thrombocytopenia with normal red and white blood cell counts is characteristic of immune thrombocytopenia (ITP).","The presence of large platelets (megathrombocytes) on peripheral blood smear is consistent with ITP.","Normal coagulation studies and liver function tests help rule out other causes of thrombocytopenia."],"references":["Bussel JB. Immune thrombocytopenia (ITP) in children: clinical features and diagnosis. In: UpToDate [online]. 2024. Available at: http://www\u200b.uptodate.com.","Faki Osman ME. Childhood immune thrombocytopenia: Clinical presentation and management. Sudan J Paediatr. 2012;12(1):27-39. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4949815/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41455"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14141"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41455"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T15:14:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T15:14:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6821"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55906"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"headi